Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with 1/4 tsp @salt{1/4%tsp} for the pasta.

Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Cut into 2cm chunks and pop onto a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with salt and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until softened, ~{15-18%minutes}.

While the pepper chunks roast, add the @linguine{180%g} to your pan of boiling water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the saucepan. Drizzle with oil and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat.

Once the oil is hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{1%pack}, @diced chorizo{60%g} and @sliced mushrooms{120%g}. Fry until golden, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the garlic and stir-fry for ~{30%seconds}, then stir in the @tomato passata{1%carton}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and @water{50%ml} for the sauce. Season with salt and pepper. Bring to the boil and simmer until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once the sauce has thickened, combine the roasted pepper, cooked pasta and sauce in whichever pan is the largest.

Stir in half the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%g}, adding a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Season to taste with salt and pepper if needed.

Share your chicken and chorizo linguine between your bowls.

Sprinkle with the remaining cheese to finish. Enjoy!